  "prompt": "Does the government have laws against money laundering?",
  "response": "Yes, the U.S. government has comprehensive laws against money laundering. The primary laws are:\n\n*   **The Bank Secrecy Act (BSA) of 1970:** This is the cornerstone of U.S. anti-money laundering (AML) efforts. It requires financial institutions to keep records and file reports on certain financial transactions that could be indicative of money laundering or other financial crimes.\n\n*   **The Money Laundering Control Act of 1986:** This act criminalized money laundering at the federal level. It prohibits engaging in financial transactions with funds derived from specified unlawful activities (SUAs), also known as predicate offenses, with the intent to conceal the source, ownership, or control of the funds.\n\n*   **The USA PATRIOT Act of 2001:** Enacted in response to the September 11th attacks, this act significantly strengthened AML laws. It broadened the scope of the BSA, enhanced due diligence requirements for financial institutions, and increased information sharing among law enforcement agencies.\n\nThese laws, along with subsequent amendments and regulations, form the basis of the U.S. AML regime. They impose obligations on financial institutions and other businesses to detect and prevent money laundering, and they provide law enforcement with the tools to investigate and prosecute money laundering offenses.",
